Title: The Lute Player
Description: Painted about 1628 Signed F.H.;  From the Coll. of Charles Jennens Esq. & mentioned as his property in the English Connoiseur of 1766 under the title of The Lutineot. Charles Jennens was an eccentric millionaire of the 18th century & a friend of Dr Johnson. also a friend & patron of Handel;  He lived at Ormond S. Red Lion Suqre London & Gopsal Leicestershire. He died unmarried Nov. 20 1773. He bequeathed his library & a large collection of works of art to his relative W. Penn Assheton Curzon (an ancestor of Earl Howe) & the Earl of Anglesford. Coll. of Earl Howe Exh. Old Masters R.A. 1884 nº90;  Extract from the Atheneum Jan. 12 1884 p.61. This peer's (Earl Howe) most masculine looking young man playing a guitar (nº20) by Frans Hals, a work so fine & firm, so broad, so full of of animation that it demands special notice at a tione when the charming but somewhat boneless art of Gainsboro, the generalized craftmanship of reynolds are influencing the public. The Hals is perhaps the most Spontan

The painting was sent to London to be hung in the Italian Embassy in 1933, but came back in 1938 to be exhibited in Venice. It was recorded in the Inventory of Card. Emanuele Pio di Savoia of 1624 (See Getty Provenance Index Databases, I-3667)  Before 1924, it was in the Lechi Collection in Brescia, then in Sir Thomas Lawrence's collection in London, then in Potter Palmer's collection in Chicago. Knoedler & Co .: Two notes: one in Paris on 9 October 1961 and one from 9 October 1961, from New York, for Un tableau par BRAM VAN VELDE / huile sur toile / Format 120 'and' One Painting by BRAM VAN VELDE, 1961 / oil on canvas, size 120 (nº PS.20).  Both notes include the amount of NF (NF = Nederlandse Florijnen = Dutch Guilder): 60.000, but the note from New York states that it should paid in dollars.
